I&#x27;m a little confused by something. I wouldn&#x27;t have expected his&#x2F;her example code to compile:<p><pre><code>  fun divide(dividend: Int, divisor: Int): Try&lt;Int, String&gt; =
      when (divisor) {
          0 -&gt; Try.Err(&quot;Cannot divide by zero!&quot;)
          else -&gt; Try.Ok(dividend &#x2F; divisor)
      }
</code></pre>
The first branch of `when` is of type `Try&lt;Nothing, String&gt;`, the second branch is `Try&lt;Int, Nothing&gt;`, and the return value is supposed to be `Try&lt;Int, String&gt;`. None of those line up...<p>How is that possible? Does the compiler do some magic for the `Nothing` type? The definition looks pretty damn simple:<p><pre><code>  public class Nothing private constructor()</code></pre>
